00:00:06.214 --> 00:00:07.660
LASZLO SYROP: All right.

00:00:07.660 --> 00:00:11.090
Well thank you, Regina, for
having us and hosting us,

00:00:11.090 --> 00:00:13.960
and for the kind words.

00:00:13.960 --> 00:00:17.060
Before I get started, I'll
do a quick presentation.

00:00:17.060 --> 00:00:19.410
But just to give you a
sense of my background,

00:00:19.410 --> 00:00:21.700
I graduated in May
from the Wharton School

00:00:21.700 --> 00:00:23.270
at the University
of Pennsylvania.

00:00:23.270 --> 00:00:25.720
And before that, I worked
in management consulting

00:00:25.720 --> 00:00:28.040
at BCG and in private equity.

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:30.010
I graduated from
Brown University.

00:00:30.010 --> 00:00:33.180
I grew up in Los Angeles,
and I now live in New York.

00:00:33.180 --> 00:00:35.839
I'll try and take a
very short 10 minutes

00:00:35.839 --> 00:00:37.630
to just give you a
little bit of background

00:00:37.630 --> 00:00:40.540
on our organization,
the Wharton 22s.

00:00:40.540 --> 00:00:45.740
And hopefully that will lead to
a rich discussion between all

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:48.140
of us and all of you.

00:00:48.140 --> 00:00:51.110
So who are the Wharton 22s?

00:00:51.110 --> 00:00:54.300
As Regina mentioned, we
are a student-led group

00:00:54.300 --> 00:00:55.930
of Wharton MBAs.

00:00:55.930 --> 00:00:57.930
Our membership is
all-male, and we

00:00:57.930 --> 00:00:59.980
work in close concert
with the Wharton Women

00:00:59.980 --> 00:01:02.040
in Business
Association, or WWIB,

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:08.470
who are Wharton's premier
women's affinity group.

00:01:08.470 --> 00:01:12.380
Because it always comes up,
I'll tackle it early-- the name.

00:01:12.380 --> 00:01:15.300
Our name, the Wharton 22s, is
a tongue-in-cheek reference

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:18.960
to the current pay gap between
men and women in America.

00:01:18.960 --> 00:01:23.560
The average-- median woman makes
22% less than the median man.

00:01:23.560 --> 00:01:26.690
And yes, it is a little
bit of a weird name.

00:01:26.690 --> 00:01:28.780
I won't take credit
for it myself.

00:01:28.780 --> 00:01:31.990
And it's not the only issue
that we concern ourselves with.

00:01:31.990 --> 00:01:33.890
But it is a great
opportunity for us

00:01:33.890 --> 00:01:37.690
to start a dialogue
about gender issues

00:01:37.690 --> 00:01:39.790
when we introduce ourselves
to a new audience.

00:01:43.290 --> 00:01:47.710
We have 34 male officers
and 320 pledged supporters.

00:01:47.710 --> 00:01:50.750
And when we talk about
pledged supporters,

00:01:50.750 --> 00:01:53.070
this is the pledge that
we're referring to.

00:01:53.070 --> 00:01:55.630
I'll let you all
read it for yourself,

00:01:55.630 --> 00:01:58.160
but essentially it boils down
to three basic commitments

00:01:58.160 --> 00:01:59.710
we ask of men at Wharton.

00:01:59.710 --> 00:02:02.130
And that's a commitment
to support gender equity

00:02:02.130 --> 00:02:04.830
efforts around us, a
commitment to understand

00:02:04.830 --> 00:02:08.300
our own role and
our own actions,

00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:12.290
and a commitment to connect
productively with others.

00:02:12.290 --> 00:02:15.830
And through our
efforts, to date,

00:02:15.830 --> 00:02:23.450
the 320 male pledgees of
the 22s represent about 1/3

00:02:23.450 --> 00:02:25.690
of all men at Wharton.

00:02:25.690 --> 00:02:28.800
We the 22s hope to see a more
equitable world with respect

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:29.727
to gender issues.

00:02:29.727 --> 00:02:31.810
And we recognize that the
business community plays

00:02:31.810 --> 00:02:34.090
a vital role in shaping that.

00:02:34.090 --> 00:02:37.710
Unfortunately, there's still a
lot of progress yet to be done.

00:02:37.710 --> 00:02:40.400
Recognizing both that
men are frequently

00:02:40.400 --> 00:02:44.000
the sources of gender
inequity and that many parts

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.680
of the business world are
currently disproportionately

00:02:46.680 --> 00:02:50.950
male, we feel that
male-led activism

00:02:50.950 --> 00:02:53.070
can be an effective
complement to the efforts

00:02:53.070 --> 00:02:54.460
of our female counterparts.

00:02:54.460 --> 00:02:58.570
And this is an idea, frankly,
that we can't take credit for.

00:02:58.570 --> 00:03:02.690
The Wharton 22s was
initially founded

00:03:02.690 --> 00:03:05.960
with the support of WWIB,
who saw this as an area

00:03:05.960 --> 00:03:07.970
for growth and
engagement, and sought out

00:03:07.970 --> 00:03:09.500
a group of male
leaders on campus

00:03:09.500 --> 00:03:13.450
to help foster these efforts.

00:03:13.450 --> 00:03:16.580
That said, our ethos is one of
recognizing that privilege--

00:03:16.580 --> 00:03:18.490
and in our case,
male privilege--

00:03:18.490 --> 00:03:20.630
imposes more obligations.

00:03:20.630 --> 00:03:22.630
As men, we inhabit
spheres where women may

00:03:22.630 --> 00:03:25.256
be absent or underrepresented.

00:03:25.256 --> 00:03:26.630
And as men, we
have opportunities

00:03:26.630 --> 00:03:30.000
to engage men who may be
resistant to women's voices.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.040
Lastly, as men, we often benefit
from an unequal status quo.

00:03:34.040 --> 00:03:37.210
And for those of us who
are involved in the 22s,

00:03:37.210 --> 00:03:41.721
we recognize an obligation to
help change that status quo.

00:03:41.721 --> 00:03:43.220
So that's a very
high-level overview

00:03:43.220 --> 00:03:45.830
of who we are as the 22s.

00:03:45.830 --> 00:03:49.092
But why are we relevant
for a company like Google?

00:03:49.092 --> 00:03:51.050
I would argue that the
challenges that we faced

00:03:51.050 --> 00:03:54.130
in forming, organizing, and
sustaining our organization

00:03:54.130 --> 00:03:56.080
are actually very similar
to the ones that you

00:03:56.080 --> 00:03:59.650
would face at Google, or frankly
at any large organization.

00:03:59.650 --> 00:04:01.150
And because of that,
our experiences

00:04:01.150 --> 00:04:03.275
can be valuable for the
community here as you think

00:04:03.275 --> 00:04:05.550
through whether this is a
strategy you want to pursue

00:04:05.550 --> 00:04:07.680
and, if so, how you
might go about doing it.

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:11.330
There are five specific areas
that I would highlight quickly

00:04:11.330 --> 00:04:13.560
which we've grappled
with in building the 22s.

00:04:13.560 --> 00:04:15.894
And I'm going to cover
them pretty quickly,

00:04:15.894 --> 00:04:17.810
but hopefully we can
continue to build on some

00:04:17.810 --> 00:04:19.470
of these in our discussion.

00:04:19.470 --> 00:04:23.310
So first is the existential
question of representation.

00:04:23.310 --> 00:04:25.630
What does it mean to
be a male ally, what

00:04:25.630 --> 00:04:27.300
does it mean to be
an ally, and what's

00:04:27.300 --> 00:04:30.930
the role of men in a
conversation that primarily

00:04:30.930 --> 00:04:31.950
affects women.

00:04:31.950 --> 00:04:34.240
How do we stand
up for the issues

00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:37.750
that we believe need
change without drowning out

00:04:37.750 --> 00:04:41.150
the voices of women who have
been active in the discussion

00:04:41.150 --> 00:04:42.654
for so long.

00:04:42.654 --> 00:04:44.320
I think this is really
important for us.

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:46.600
And for the men in
attendance, if you leave here

00:04:46.600 --> 00:04:49.530
with one thing, I would
say remember this.

00:04:49.530 --> 00:04:54.290
Our view is that being an ally
requires humility, empathy,

00:04:54.290 --> 00:04:57.060
and courage, but
humility first of all.

00:04:57.060 --> 00:04:59.070
And that's the
humility to understand

00:04:59.070 --> 00:05:01.950
that you don't have the
same lived experience

00:05:01.950 --> 00:05:04.350
of your female allies.

00:05:04.350 --> 00:05:08.200
And rather than viewing
yourself as a change agent who

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:11.100
has all the answers, instead
see your mission as one

00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:15.010
to listen, to understand,
and to support.

00:05:15.010 --> 00:05:17.410
I think, you know, just
to reiterate one thing,

00:05:17.410 --> 00:05:19.290
which is in the
business community,

00:05:19.290 --> 00:05:21.500
and I think particularly
in technology,

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:25.810
there's an attitude that
coming with a solution first,

00:05:25.810 --> 00:05:29.190
being willing to move
fast and break things,

00:05:29.190 --> 00:05:31.410
is the solution
to all situations.

00:05:31.410 --> 00:05:36.190
And I think that often we
forget that, in social issues,

00:05:36.190 --> 00:05:39.510
sometimes listening, taking
a step back, admitting what

00:05:39.510 --> 00:05:41.690
we don't know, and being
willing to be wrong

00:05:41.690 --> 00:05:43.180
and being willing
to be vulnerable

00:05:43.180 --> 00:05:45.850
can be even more impactful.

00:05:45.850 --> 00:05:48.520
Second, and more practically,
the question of recruitment.

00:05:48.520 --> 00:05:50.920
How do you get men to care
about this issue who should

00:05:50.920 --> 00:05:53.460
be part of a male ally group.

00:05:53.460 --> 00:05:56.280
We take a multi-pronged approach
here to the work that we do,

00:05:56.280 --> 00:05:59.650
and we try to appeal to
men on multiple levels,

00:05:59.650 --> 00:06:03.980
ranging from the pure
ethical-- the purely ethical

00:06:03.980 --> 00:06:05.320
to the more self-interested.

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:07.270
Some of the things we
emphasize at Wharton

00:06:07.270 --> 00:06:10.920
are the ability to be
an inclusive leader

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:12.290
and collaborator in teams.

00:06:12.290 --> 00:06:14.590
I think there was an era
where the idea of being

00:06:14.590 --> 00:06:17.870
a global manager was new to
the business school curriculum.

00:06:17.870 --> 00:06:20.260
And where we are
today, I see the view

00:06:20.260 --> 00:06:23.430
of being an inclusive leader at
the forefront of what it means

00:06:23.430 --> 00:06:25.970
to be a successful manager.

00:06:25.970 --> 00:06:27.470
Additionally, we'd
like to emphasize

00:06:27.470 --> 00:06:29.190
that these are not
purely women's issues

00:06:29.190 --> 00:06:30.080
that we talk about.

00:06:30.080 --> 00:06:32.890
Family leave policies
can affect both men

00:06:32.890 --> 00:06:34.210
and women in the workplace.

00:06:34.210 --> 00:06:36.420
And we also address questions
of work/life balance

00:06:36.420 --> 00:06:38.519
for men, the
question of what does

00:06:38.519 --> 00:06:39.810
it mean to be an active father.

00:06:39.810 --> 00:06:43.270
How do you address
issues of masculinity.

00:06:43.270 --> 00:06:45.800
And then lastly, it's obviously
the right thing to do.

00:06:45.800 --> 00:06:48.230
And I think most people's
hearts are in the right place,

00:06:48.230 --> 00:06:52.160
and we hope to help equip
them with better tools

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:55.710
to be that change they
want to see in the world.

00:06:55.710 --> 00:06:57.700
Third, programming.

00:06:57.700 --> 00:07:00.390
What do we actually do
as a male ally group,

00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:03.162
and what tangible
measures do we take.

00:07:03.162 --> 00:07:04.960
We have a basic
framework for how

00:07:04.960 --> 00:07:08.100
we try to engage with
our audience at Wharton.

00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:12.100
And that includes awareness,
dialogue, and activism.

00:07:12.100 --> 00:07:15.430
For each of these, we try
to develop programming

00:07:15.430 --> 00:07:19.060
relevant for folks at
Wharton to-- first, to build

00:07:19.060 --> 00:07:21.730
their awareness that gender
inequities still exist,

00:07:21.730 --> 00:07:25.270
and what those are;
to foster dialogue,

00:07:25.270 --> 00:07:27.150
to help them connect
with their peers,

00:07:27.150 --> 00:07:30.780
and to listen to the experiences
of their female counterparts;

00:07:30.780 --> 00:07:32.370
and to empower them
to be effective

00:07:32.370 --> 00:07:35.960
advocates for change in the
environments they go into.

00:07:35.960 --> 00:07:38.562
In terms of awareness,
we publish articles

00:07:38.562 --> 00:07:39.520
in The Wharton Journal.

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:41.310
We invite speakers to campus.

00:07:41.310 --> 00:07:43.960
We employ social media
campaigns to raise awareness

00:07:43.960 --> 00:07:46.320
of various gender issues.

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:48.090
And we have Lunch
Lecture series so people

00:07:48.090 --> 00:07:52.850
can feel educated about
the topics that we discuss.

00:07:52.850 --> 00:07:55.880
To foster dialogue, we host
Candid Dinner Discussion

00:07:55.880 --> 00:07:58.119
series, where people
can have a safe space

00:07:58.119 --> 00:08:00.160
to engage on these topics
and feel that they have

00:08:00.160 --> 00:08:02.076
a forum within the
business school community

00:08:02.076 --> 00:08:03.700
and within the
professional environment

00:08:03.700 --> 00:08:05.570
to talk about these
types of issues.

00:08:05.570 --> 00:08:08.400
And we host workshops to
help people understand

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:10.890
the various ways that
intersectionality can play

00:08:10.890 --> 00:08:12.980
into this mission, as well.

00:08:12.980 --> 00:08:16.600
And lastly, in terms of
activism, the first step

00:08:16.600 --> 00:08:19.760
we have is having the existence
of the 22s and our officer

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:22.270
board so that men who are
interested in the subject

00:08:22.270 --> 00:08:24.220
can get more involved,
and progressively

00:08:24.220 --> 00:08:27.870
continue to get involved in
the issue of gender equity.

00:08:27.870 --> 00:08:30.180
And secondly, we have
intensive workshops

00:08:30.180 --> 00:08:33.919
where we work on empowering
MBA candidates with the tools

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:35.570
to make change
and intervene when

00:08:35.570 --> 00:08:40.020
they return to the real world
and their professional lives.

00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:42.179
Fourth, the topic of discomfort.

00:08:42.179 --> 00:08:43.940
How do you manage
the awkward and often

00:08:43.940 --> 00:08:46.650
threatening feelings that
can come with engaging

00:08:46.650 --> 00:08:48.000
on a touchy subject.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.160
All of our work hopes
to create a climate

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:55.080
where folks feel safe discussing
these issues, empowered

00:08:55.080 --> 00:08:58.382
to ask questions, and
comfortable being vulnerable.

00:08:58.382 --> 00:09:00.090
But I think the biggest
impact that we've

00:09:00.090 --> 00:09:02.680
had in creating this type
of an outcome at Wharton

00:09:02.680 --> 00:09:05.510
is by existing as a group,
by setting an example

00:09:05.510 --> 00:09:07.600
that this is an
appropriate conversation

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:11.180
topic, by acting as role models
for other men who might want

00:09:11.180 --> 00:09:15.630
to engage on the topic, and
creating a critical mass that

00:09:15.630 --> 00:09:18.790
shows the outside world that
this is a topic of interest

00:09:18.790 --> 00:09:21.750
to young business leaders.

00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:23.740
And lastly, what's
the best structure

00:09:23.740 --> 00:09:24.950
for a group like this.

00:09:24.950 --> 00:09:27.317
How do you continue to
sustain an organization

00:09:27.317 --> 00:09:29.150
like this, particularly
in a business school

00:09:29.150 --> 00:09:32.790
environment, where we
have 50% annual turnover.

00:09:32.790 --> 00:09:35.520
I think today these are
probably the areas where

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:37.800
we have the most to grow.

00:09:37.800 --> 00:09:39.700
But luckily, being
in business school,

00:09:39.700 --> 00:09:41.533
we have a lot of
opportunities to experiment

00:09:41.533 --> 00:09:42.916
and try to get the model right.

00:09:42.916 --> 00:09:45.839
I know 10 minutes probably isn't
enough time to familiarize you

00:09:45.839 --> 00:09:48.130
with everything that we've
done and all of the thinking

00:09:48.130 --> 00:09:51.420
that we've done about the issue
of being a male ally group,

00:09:51.420 --> 00:09:53.150
but hopefully this
gives you a little bit

00:09:53.150 --> 00:09:57.090
of a taste for our work, how
we think about our mission,

00:09:57.090 --> 00:09:59.050
and leads to a
good conversation.

00:09:59.050 --> 00:10:02.234
So with that, I'll thank
you for hosting us today.

00:10:02.234 --> 00:10:04.150
It's really a pleasure
to have the opportunity

00:10:04.150 --> 00:10:06.680
